title: Introduction to RGCxGC package
text: vignette explain implementation RGCxGC package. text presents end--end pipeline analysis comprehensive two dimensional gas chromatography (GCxGC-MS) data. can access specific function help command help([‘function name’]). general workflow signal preprocessing chromatography summarized Figure 1. Raw chromatographic signals usually contains undesirable artifacts, chemical instrumental noise. Therefore, noise data removed prior statistical analysis. Furthermore, noise can significantly reduced using preprocessing algorithms, herein smoothing, baseline correction, peak alignment. , order reveal differences groups, multivariate analysis can performed. Figure 1. Overview general data processing pipeline chromatography presented RGCxGC package. RGCxGC package, first, raw chromatogram importing NetCDF file folded two-dimensional Total Intensity Chromatogram (2D-TIC). Next, can perform three preprocessing methodologies order enhance signals, smooth, baseline correction, peak alignment. Basically, smooth enhance signal noise ratio (S/N), baseline correction handles column blooding, peak alignment corrects retention time shift peaks across multiple runs. Finally, can perform multiway principal component analysis (MPCA) look systematic patterns distinguish samples.

title: Introduction to RGCxGC package
text: Whittaker smoother algorithm1 used package (Eilers 2003). main advantages, accounts computational efficiency, control smoothness automatically interpolation. Whittaker smoother GCxGC implemented first chromatogram dimension. words, smoothing carry every chromatographic modulation. Whittaker smooth algorithm works discrete penalized least squares. instance, penalty order (1 2) \(\lambda\) arguments provided. penalty refers order penalize roughness signals, \(\lambda\) factor multiply rougness signal level. instance, greater parameter values hava stronger influence smmothing process.
code: # Linear penalty with lambda equal to 10 MTBLS08_sm1 <- wsmooth(MTBLS08_bc, penalty = 1, lambda = 1e1) plot(MTBLS08_sm1, nlevels = 100, color.palette = matlab.like,      main = expression(paste(lambda, "= 10, penalty = 1")) ) # Cuadratic penalty with lambda equal to 10 MTBLS08_sm2 <- wsmooth(MTBLS08_bc, penalty = 2, lambda = 1e1) plot(MTBLS08_sm2, nlevels = 100, color.palette = matlab.like,      main = expression(paste(lambda, "= 10, penalty = 2")) )

title: Introduction to RGCxGC package
text: chemometric pipeline, user selects desired required preprocessing steps. However, peak alignment practically mandatory whenever multiple samples compared. peak alignment corrects unavoidable shifts retention times among chromatographic runs. two general pathways peak alignment: using peak table, pixel level alignment. package, pixel level alignment implemented using two-dimensional correlation optimized warping (2D-COW) algorithm implemented (Dabao Zhang et al. 2008). Basically, algorithm works splitting raw chromatogram \(n\) segments. , time warping applied dimensions using one dimensional correlation optimized warping (COW) algorithm (Tomasi, Van Den Berg, Andersson 2004). TwoDCOW function need four arguments: sample name, reference chromatogram, number segments split chromatogram maximum warping level dimensions.
code: # Reference chromatogram chrom_09 <- system.file("extdata", "09GB.cdf", package = "RGCxGC") MTBLS09 <- read_chrom(chrom_09, mod_time = 5L) ## Warning in base_GCxGC(Object = Object, mod_time = mod_time, sam_rate = ## sam_rate, : The last 51 signals will be omitted ## Warning in matrix(tic, nrow = len_1d, ncol = len_2d): data length [61051] is not ## a sub-multiple or multiple of the number of rows [500] ## Retention time ranges: ## 1D (min): 7.98 18.16  ## 2D (sec): 0 5  ## Acquisition rate: 100 # Baseline correction MTBL09_bc <- baseline_corr(MTBLS09) # Smoothing MTBL09_sm2 <- wsmooth(MTBL09_bc, penalty = 2, lambda = 1e1) # Alignment  aligned <- twod_cow(sample_chrom = MTBLS08_sm2, ref_chrom =  MTBL09_sm2,                    segments = c(10, 40), max_warp = c(1, 8)) plot(aligned, nlevels = 100, color.palette = matlab.like,      main = "Aligned chromatogram")
